\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Jech,
 I.7.27
\end_layout

\end_inset

The following distributive law holds in a complete Boolean algebra:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\land\bigvee_{y\in Y}y=\bigvee_{y\in Y}\left(x\land y\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
(You didn't ask us to prove this,
 but I wanted to anyway.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
One inequality is obvious:
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\lor Y\geq y$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\land\lor Y\geq x\land y$
\end_inset

,
 and taking the sup on the RHS we get 
\begin_inset Formula $x\land\bigvee_{y\in Y}y\geq\bigvee_{y\in Y}\left(x\land y\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We turn to proving the other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Let us assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is an upper bound of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\land y$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula $u\lor\neg x\geq(x\land y)\lor\neg x=y\lor\neg x\geq y$
\end_inset

.
 Hence,
 
\begin_inset Formula $u\lor\neg x\geq\lor Y$
\end_inset

,
 and so we conclude 
\begin_inset Formula $u\geq u\land x=(u\lor\neg x)\land x\geq x\land\lor Y$
\end_inset

.
 Since this holds of any upper bound in particular,
 it also holds of 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\lor_{y\in Y}(x\land y)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\land\bigvee_{y\in Y}y\leq\bigvee_{y\in Y}\left(x\land y\right)$
\end_inset

 as desired.
\end_layout

