\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Kunen,
 VII.D1
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

-complete Boolean algebra in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq B$
\end_inset

.
 Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

-generic iff 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is an ultrafilter and,
 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $S\in\powerset(B)^{M}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lor S\in F$
\end_inset

,
 we there is an element 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S\cap F$
\end_inset

.
 [I'm translating terms a little bit here.
 But I am confident that this is equivalent.]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
First,
 suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

-generic.
 We show that 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is an ultrafilter.
 To this effect,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B$
\end_inset

,
 and we shall show that either 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg x$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Consider the set:
 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{x}=\{y\in B^{+}\mid y\leq x\text{ or }y\land x=0\}$
\end_inset

.
 It is dense because,
 for any given 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

,
 either 
\begin_inset Formula $z\land x=0$
\end_inset

,
 in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is already in 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{x}$
\end_inset

,
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $z\land x\neq0$
\end_inset

,
 in which case we have found an element 
\begin_inset Formula $y=z\land x$
\end_inset

 that extends 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 and is in 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{x}\in M$
\end_inset

 by comprehension.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Now,
 let's use this to show that either 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg x$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 meets every 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

-set,
 there must be 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in F\cap D_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 either 
\begin_inset Formula $y\leq x$
\end_inset

,
 in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in M$
\end_inset

,
 or we have 
\begin_inset Formula $y\land x=0$
\end_inset

.
 Some Boolean algebra manipulations will then show that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\leq\neg x$
\end_inset

,
 in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg x\in F$
\end_inset

,
 as desired.
 Here are the manipulations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y\land\underbrace{(x\lor\neg x)}_{1}=y\implies\cancel{(y\land x)}\lor(y\land\neg x)=y\implies y\land\neg x=y\implies y\leq\neg x.
\]

\end_inset

It then remains to prove the second part.
 Thus,
 suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lor S\in F$
\end_inset

.
 We consider the dense set 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 given by :
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

All the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 that are below some element of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

,
 or incompatible with every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This set is dense as follows:
 A given 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B$
\end_inset

 is either incompatible with every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

,
 in which case it's already in 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

,
 or it's compatible with some 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

,
 in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $x\land s\leq x$
\end_inset

 is an extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Pick 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in D\land F$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is below some element of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

,
 then that element is in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and the proof is done.
 Otherwise,
 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is incompatible with every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

,
 and by distributivity,
 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigvee_{s\in S}(d\land s)=0\implies\left(\vee S\right)\land d=0,
\]

\end_inset

which contradicts the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a filter in 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{+}$
\end_inset

,
 as there will be no least upper bound to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lor S\in F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in F$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 the first implication is complete.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset

For the other implication,
 suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is an ultrafilter in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 (and so,
 in particular,
 a filter) such that,
 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $S\in M$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lor S\in F$
\end_inset

,
 there is an element 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S\cap F$
\end_inset

.
 Now,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $D\in M$
\end_inset

 be a dense set.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lor D=1$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed,
 we note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg\lor D$
\end_inset

,
 if nonzero,
 must be above some element 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in D$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg d\geq\lor D\geq d$
\end_inset

,
 whence 
\begin_inset Formula $d=0$
\end_inset

,
 a contradiction with 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in D$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
If 
\begin_inset Formula $D\in M$
\end_inset

 is a dense set,
 we then have 
\begin_inset Formula $\lor D=1$
\end_inset

,
 which is in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 by assumption,
 there must be an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Since this holds for every dense 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

-set,
 we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a generic filter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
(To the best of my understanding,
 the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is an 
\emph on
ultra
\emph default
filter is only used in Kunen's wording of the problem to discuss the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

associated homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Kunen,
 VII.D2
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 be a Boolean algebra,
 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{S_{n}\}_{n\in\N}$
\end_inset

 be a family of subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 with suprema,
 say 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Show that there is a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon B\to2$
\end_inset

 such that,
 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\N$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(b_{n})=\lor_{s\in S_{n}}f(s)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
This is the same as to build an ultrafilter 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

,
 such that,
 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}\in F$
\end_inset

,
 there is some 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S_{n}\cap F$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
To begin,
 we build a decreasing sequence of nonzero elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g_{n}\}_{n\in\N}$
\end_inset

 that will be used to build a special filter,
 which guarantees this condition on the 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we shall simply use Zorn's lemma or whatever other version of choice we prefer,
 to extend this filter into an ultrafilter.
 This ultrafilter will satisfy the desired condition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Set 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{0}=1$
\end_inset

,
 and,
 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
 ask the question:
 Is 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}\land g_{n}=0$
\end_inset

?
 If so,
 then it must be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg b_{n}\land g_{n}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero,
 so we set that to be 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 If not,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\lor_{s\in S_{n}}s\right)\land g_{n}=g_{n}\neq0$
\end_inset

,
 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigvee_{s\in S_{n}}(s\land g_{n})\neq0$
\end_inset

,
 and so there is some specific 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S_{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s\land g_{n}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 We set 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{n+1}=s\land g_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Now,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{0}$
\end_inset

 be the filter of elements that are above some 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{n}$
\end_inset

,
 and extend it to an ultrafilter 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that this ultrafilter does what we want it to do.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
To this effect,
 suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}\in F$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 at step 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
 when defining 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 we 
\emph on
cannot
\emph default
 have chosen to set 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{n+1}=\neg b_{n}\land g_{n}$
\end_inset

:
 Otherwise,
 it'd be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg b_{n}\in F_{0}\subseteq F$
\end_inset

,
 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in F$
\end_inset

,
 a contradiction.
 Thus,
 at stage 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
 we chose a specific element 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S_{n}$
\end_inset

 to take the join with 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 As such,
 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in F_{0}\subseteq F$
\end_inset

.
 In other words:
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}\in F$
\end_inset

,
 there is 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S_{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in F$
\end_inset

,
 which completes the proof.
\end_layout

