\begin_inset Formula $\neg x\in\dot{G}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first property is obvious because 
\begin_inset Formula $\Norm{\check{x}\in\dot{G}}=x$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in G$
\end_inset

,
 and in particular for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

.
 (Technically:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Norm{\check{x}\in\dot{G}}=\lor_{t\in\dom\dot{G}}(\Norm{\check{x}=t}\land\dot{G}(t))$
\end_inset

 ,
 but the only relevant term in this disjunction is 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\check{x}$
\end_inset

 because equality is interpreted as equality over canonical names and the domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{G}$
\end_inset

 consists only of canonical names.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second property we show as follows:
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are terms,
 we estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\Norm{(x\land y)\in\dot{G}}$
\end_inset

 by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Norm{(x\land y)\in\dot{G}} & =\bigvee_{z\in G}\Norm{(x\land y)=\check{z}}\geq\bigvee_{z,a,b\in G}\left(\Norm{(x\land y)=(\check{a}\land\check{b})}\land\Norm{\check{a}\land\check{b}=\check{z}}\right)\\
 & \geq\bigvee_{a,b\in G}\left(\Norm{x=\check{a}}\land\Norm{y=\check{b}}\right)=\Norm{x\in\dot{G}}\land\Norm{y\in\dot{G}},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The first equality is by definition,
 plus usage of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dom\dot{G}=\text{canonical names of elements of }G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{G}(\check{z})=z$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The next step consists of the equality rule 
\begin_inset Formula $\Norm{x=z}\geq\Norm{x=y}\land\Norm{y=z}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The next step consists of using the rule 
\begin_inset Formula $\Norm{\check{x}=\check{y}}$
\end_inset

 being zero or one depending on whether 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y$
\end_inset

,
 together with the fact that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in G$
\end_inset

 there is some 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in G$
\end_inset

 that makes 
\begin_inset Formula $\Norm{\check{a}\land\check{b}=\check{z}}=1$
\end_inset

,
 namely 
\begin_inset Formula $z=a\land b$
\end_inset

,
 as well as the theorem that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x=a\land y=b\right)\rightarrow\left(x\land y=a\land b\right)$
\end_inset

 to separate the equality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Finally,
 the last step uses distributivity (I checked that it's the allowed type,
 it's just annoying to write out,
 you do it in multiple steps) and the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Norm{x\in\dot{G}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So,
 this shows 
\begin_inset Formula $\Norm{x\in\dot{G}}\land\Norm{y\in\dot{G}}\leq\Norm{(x\land y)\in\dot{G}}$
\end_inset

,
 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\Norm{\left(x\in\dot{G}\land y\in\dot{G}\right)\rightarrow(x\land y)\in\dot{G}}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 the third property follows by a similar reasoning.
 The main step seems to be to use 
\begin_inset Formula $\Norm{x\in\dot{G}}=\bigvee_{z\in G}\Norm{x=\check{z}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Norm{x\in\check{B}}=\bigvee_{z\in B}\Norm{x=\check{z}}$
\end_inset

 and then reason about 
