\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Kunen,
 VII.G4
\end_layout

\end_inset

Consider the following notion of forcing:
 Partial functions 
\begin_inset Formula $I\rightharpoonup2$
\end_inset

 with countable domain,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is uncountable.
 Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $M[G]$
\end_inset

 satisfies CH.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
First,
 I claim that,
 since this notion of forcing is 
\begin_inset Formula $\aleph_{1}$
\end_inset

-closed,
 no new reals are added.
 This probably follows straight up from stuff said in class,
 but just in case:
 Given a name for a real in 
\begin_inset Formula $(2^{\aleph_{0}})^{M[G]}$
\end_inset

,
 take a countable set of conditions that force its first entry,
 its second entry,
 etc.
 Then,
 taking the (countable) union of all these forcing conditions,
 we get a forcing condition (in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

) that forces all the entry of the real,
 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 already had the real all along.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Moreover,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is the generic,
 we define 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\cup G$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon\omega_{1}\times\omega\to I$
\end_inset

 be an injective function (in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

).
 Then,
 we claim that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g\colon\omega_{1}\to2^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\alpha)(n)=F(f(\alpha,n))$
\end_inset

 is a surjective function from 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\aleph_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 We do this by showing that,
 for any real 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in(2^{\aleph_{0}})^{M}$
\end_inset

,
 the condition 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{im}g$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is dense.
 Then,
 we use the fact that the reals in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 are the same as the reals in 
\begin_inset Formula $M[G]$
\end_inset

,
 to obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is surjective from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\omega_{1}\right)^{M}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2^{\aleph_{0}}\right)^{M[G]}$
\end_inset

.
 This will give us our conclusion,
 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}^{M[G]}$
\end_inset

 surjects onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}^{M}$
\end_inset

 no matter the forcing extension (in fact,
 these wind up being the same in our case,
 because if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}^{M}$
\end_inset

 was countable in 
\begin_inset Formula $M[G]$
\end_inset

 we would have 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\aleph_{0}}$
\end_inset

 countable in 
