\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Kunen,
 VII.G7
\end_layout

\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 satisfies CH,
 and consider Cohen forcing with domain 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\card I\geq\aleph_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Show that Martin's axiom fails in 
\begin_inset Formula $M[G]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Kunen suggests applying Exercise II.8,
 which states that,
 assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\MA$
\end_inset

,
 for any set of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\to\omega$
\end_inset

 of size less than 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\aleph_{0}}$
\end_inset

,
 there is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\to\omega$
\end_inset

 that dominates all of them.
 As such,
 this suggests showing that,
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M[G]$
\end_inset

,
 there is a family of functions of size 
\begin_inset Formula $\aleph_{1}^{M[G]}$
\end_inset

 that is not dominated by any function.
 Of course,
 we also need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $(2^{\aleph_{0}})^{M[G]}\geq\aleph_{2}^{M[G]}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Okay,
 first of all,
 if we've added a generic subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

,
 we have also added a generic subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\aleph_{2}$
\end_inset

,
 because by assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $\aleph_{2}$
\end_inset

 injects into 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 in the ground model.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\aleph_{2}$
\end_inset

 is in bijection with 
\begin_inset Formula $\aleph_{2}\times\aleph_{0}$
\end_inset

,
 we have therefore added 
\begin_inset Formula $\aleph_{2}$
\end_inset

-many generic reals,
 all distinct from each other (this is the same argument as the one used to show consistency of not-CH).
 Since this forcing condition satisfies the c.c.c,
 cardinalities are preserved and so 
\begin_inset Formula $(2^{\aleph_{0}})^{M[G]}\geq\aleph_{2}^{M[G]}=\aleph_{2}^{M}$
\end_inset

.
 (I think we actually get equality but whatever.) So,
 all we need to do now is show that there is a family of functions of size 
\begin_inset Formula $\aleph_{1}$
\end_inset

 that is not dominated by any function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be the set of all functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\to\omega$
\end_inset

 in the ground model.
 This has size 
\begin_inset Formula $(2^{\aleph_{0}})^{M}=\aleph_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 We just need to show that there is no function,
 even in 
\begin_inset Formula $M[G]$
\end_inset

,
 that dominates every function in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Intuitively,
 here's what I think.
 Pick a name 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in V^{B}$
\end_inset

 and a forcing condition 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

,
 which we suppose WLOG forces 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to be a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\to\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the function 
\begin_inset Formula $a(n)$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the smallest value 
\begin_inset Formula $f(n)$
\end_inset

 could be forced to be by an extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

,
 plus one
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This function is well-defined because,
 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 forces 
\begin_inset Formula $f(n)\in\omega$
\end_inset

,
 hence 
\begin_inset Formula $0\neq p\leq\vee_{y\in\omega}\Norm{f(n)=\check{y}}$
\end_inset

,
 and so there is some value of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $p\land\Norm{f(n)=\check{y}}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero.
 Then,
 I think that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in(2^{\omega})^{M}$
\end_inset

 is not forced to be dominated by 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Because,
 if it were,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 would force a point 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 after which 
\begin_inset Formula $a\leq f$
\end_inset

 (I think this is sketchy),
 which is a contradiction because we can take the extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 that makes 
\begin_inset Formula $f(N+1)<a(N+1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

